  <h1 class="hidetitle">Escape Routes</h1>
  <h2>Design your APIs carefully</h2>
  <h3>George Neville-Neil</h3>
  <p><b>Dear KV</b>,</p>
  <p>In a previous column, “Facing the Strain” (September 2006), you wrote about the use of an escape function. You mentioned <code>ioctl()</code>, which allows a program to get at data without as much type checking. The column where you mentioned this is pretty old now, so do you still think this is a good idea? The code I’ve seen lately that contains these escapes leads to a lot of problems, precisely because of the lack of type checking and other safety mechanisms. But one of the engineers I work with insists on starting with just such an API and only creates more specific versions when we demand them. That seems both backwards and dangerous. Have you changed your opinion of these escape hatches over time?</p>
  <p align="right" style="text-align:right"><b>Bypassed</b></p>
  <p><b>Dear Bypassed</b>,</p>
  <p>First, let me commend you for sticking with KV’s column for so many years. The passage you’re referencing is truly ancient, and—if KV hadn’t been shaving his head since his 20s—this would make me feel <i>truly</i> old. Happily, with a shaved head, no one can see the gray! Also, shaving is better than pulling my hair out, which—over the years—is something I’ve tried only to find there was nothing left to pull!</p>
  <p><img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/attachment/html/10.1145/3799735/assets/html/031226.column.neville-neil.image1.jpg" alt="image" /></p>
  <p>Anyway, it’s not so much a question of changing my opinion about leaving yourself an escape hatch. That’s still something I would encourage one to do in any design. No one wants to paint themself into a corner, even if the color is a lovely sky blue. What you seem to be describing is someone who doesn’t want to commit to a definite API and so instead is using <code>ioctl()</code> or something similar as their “I couldn’t be bothered to develop an API” API.</p>
  <p>API design is a nontrivial exercise. It requires thought and consideration for other people and their future requirements (and programmers, I believe, still qualify as people). Sometimes, it just amounts to consideration for your future self who will be faced with reusing that API later. Even if you don’t love yourself, you should learn compassion for the others who will be subjected to your code choices.</p>
  <p>Software is almost infinitely fungible, but at some point you have to make choices and pin down what you want a thing to do. This is the art of API design.</p>
  <p>Proper API design commits the programmer to a certain type of interaction: Am I passing values? Am I passing references? What are my return codes? What are the errors to be handled? How do I make my API something that can be tested? I bet the person you’re dealing with doesn’t write tests—another offense that should be punishable corporally, in KV’s view.</p>
  <p>Providing only a single function, <code>ioctl()</code> or otherwise, is the equivalent of throwing up your hands and saying, “I don’t know. Do whatever you want!”</p>
  <p>This abdication of responsibility is reprehensible. So, yeah, it pisses off KV, a <i>lot</i>.</p>
  <p>You’re also correct that it is unsafe—or, in KV’s argot, <i>stupid</i>. To make it impossible to type check what goes in and out of an API is like putting a big “KICK ME” sign on your software. And, as we’ve seen many times over recent decades, if you ask attackers to kick you, they will… <i>hard!</i> So, when one adds a proper bypass mechanism that requires code to be even more strict about refusing to do any but the narrowest tasks on behalf of the caller, this simply qualifies as a matter of proper self-defense for your code.</p>
  <p>At least for KV, the idea of starting with the most open API and then only coming back later to narrow it screams of laziness and an unwillingness to think about what one is really doing. KV loves to be lazy, but that’s not for code, only for long nights in a bad neighborhood known for its cheap drinks and loose morals. When you’re too open with your APIs, you’ll get calls from the operations team just after you’ve ordered a drink for a person down at the other end of the bar. KV prefers that his bad choices be made in real life rather than in software. Those bad life choices can be fixed with antibiotics, but bad choices in software can live on forever.</p>
  <p align="right" style="text-align:right"><b>KV</b></p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <p><b>George V. Neville-Neil</b> <i>works on networking and operating-system code for fun and profit. He also teaches courses on various subjects related to programming. His areas of interest are computer security, operating systems, networking, time protocols, and the care and feeding of large codebases. He is the author of</i> The Kollected Kode Vicious <i>and co-author with Marshall Kirk McKusick and Robert N. M. Watson of</i> The Design and Implementation of the FreeBSD Operating System. <i>For nearly 20 years he has been the columnist better known as Kode Vicious. Since 2014 he has been an industrial visitor at the University of Cambridge, where he is involved in several projects relating to computer security. He earned his bachelor’s degree in computer science at Northeastern University in Boston, Massachusetts, and is a member of the ACM, the Usenix Association, and IEEE. His software not only runs on Earth, but also has been deployed as part of VxWorks in NASA’s missions to Mars. He is an avid bicyclist and traveler who currently lives in New York City.</i></p>
